# Supply-chain cooldown: refuse to install any package version published less
# than 7 days ago. Most malicious npm releases are caught and pulled within
# hours-to-days, so a 7-day cooldown sharply cuts the blast radius of a
# compromised release landing in our tree.
#
# IMPORTANT: npm's key is `min-release-age` and the unit is DAYS.
#   - pnpm uses `minimumReleaseAge` in MINUTES (10080 = 7 days) — different!
#   - the old `minimum-release-age=10080` here was a no-op: wrong key (npm
#     ignores unknown config) AND, even corrected, 10080 would mean 10080 days.
# Requires npm >= 11.10.0; OLDER npm SILENTLY IGNORES this. engines.npm in
# package.json surfaces an "Unsupported engine" warning on too-old npm.
# No per-package exclusion exists yet (unlike pnpm); for an urgent security
# patch that is younger than the window, bypass per-install with:
#   npm i --min-release-age 0 <pkg>@<version>
min-release-age=7
